  "summary": "Hercule Poirot questions a waitress named Lucie regarding guests who made phone calls. Lucie reveals that a young lady in a white dress called upon entering, and another lady made a call from a booth after exiting the cloakroom. Poirot suspects something is about to happen.\n\nDuring the dinner, Barton Russell proposes a toast to his late wife, Eileen, who died four years ago today. He reveals that the dinner is a commemoration of her death, which occurred during a dinner in New York attended by himself, Stephen Carter, Anthony Chapple, Miss Valdes, and a sixteen-year-old Polly Weatherby. Barton explains that while the official verdict was suicide via cyanide, he believes Eileen was murdered by someone present at the New York dinner who planted cyanide in her handbag. He claims he is certain of the truth and intends to uncover it.\n\nAs the lights dim for a cabaret performance, a Black singer performs a mournful song. The atmosphere is noted as being strikingly similar to the night of the New York tragedy. After the performance, the lights return, and the guests discover that Polly Weatherby has slumped over the table, dead. Lola compares the death to that of \"Alice\" in New York. Poirot examines Polly and confirms she is dead, noting the scent of cyanide, similar to bitter almonds, in her cup. Barton Russell expresses distress, suggesting Polly may have seen something suspicious during the original incident.",
